    {
      "id": "c2642edef12adbceed10e794cefb4d111db8190e",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 119,
        "name": "Alex Zhuravlev",
        "email": "bzzz@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "bzzz"
      },
      "date": "2013-01-24 07:11:27.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nI do understand compatibility issue you got. and I rised this issue in the ticket before. but I also think that putting different parameters into different properties is not that good because literally it means mount_utils_zfs.c should be aware of all parameters. and one, adding a parameter to lustre, would need to make sure it's properly supported in mount_utils_zfs.c as well. I find this risky. I'd think that in general lustre parameters should be controlled by lustre utility.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "0af520914df8499e9c4d64f56f994d58efeb6fd6",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 119,
        "name": "Alex Zhuravlev",
        "email": "bzzz@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "bzzz"
      },
      "date": "2013-01-24 11:34:20.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1: Looks good to me, but someone else must approve\n\n",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "265626954961d6aba6c25038e3b6b6221bb622e8",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 124,
        "name": "Prakash Surya",
        "email": "lists@prakashsurya.com",
        "username": "prakash"
      },
      "date": "2013-01-24 17:14:31.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nAlex, yes, adding a parameter would mean modifying mount_utils_zfs.c. Why do you say this is \"risky\"? Sure it presents a higher bar for entry when changing the parameters, but I don't think this is a bad thing. Wouldn't the modules need to be changed to recognize a new parameter anyways?\n\nAnd we can require users to use the lustre utils from the same tag/version as the lustre modules they are running. Ensuring the utils always matches what the modules expect.\n\nThe HUGE win we get from using separate parameters are:\n    1. It's much easier to administer the values (inspect,\n       modify, delete, etc.), and\n    2. More straight forward code for handling parameters\n       (no complicated string parsing)\n\nOnce all of the necessary parameter handling is implemented, it's straight forward enough to add/remove parameter recognition by modifying the mount files as you mentioned.\n\nIs there something more fundamental that I am missing?",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "4d3df3beb91ad8dfc3637712cef705be68ab574a",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 192,
        "name": "Brian Behlendorf",
        "email": "behlendorf1@llnl.gov",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2013-01-24 18:22:40.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1: Looks good to me, but someone else must approve\n\nI would argue that the 'risky' thing to do here is to keep them all in a single string.\n\nThis seems like a good idea on the surface.  But we've found that in practice with ldiskfs it increases the likelyhood of an error when changing the configuration.   This is largely because all the options are always modified and it's very easy to accidentally drop one, or modify one, or add one you didn't mean too.  Keeping them separate makes it easier to spot check you got it right and limits the damage when you didn't.\n\nOur system administrators agree that keeping them separate is far preferable from a manageability standpoint.  And this is really the perspective we need to keep in mind when developing all of the user visible interfaces.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "cd38a277b1a2486711f781341579d73e0a359061",
      "author": {
